font-weight: normal;">ligament usually secondary to low-grade in</span><span style="font-size: 9pt; font-style: italic; background-color: initial; font-weight: normal; font-family: &quot;AdvTT31ea7dbe+fb&quot;;">fl</span><span style="font-family: AdvTT31ea7dbe; font-size: 9pt; font-style: italic; background-color: initial; font-weight: normal;">ammation and&nbsp;</span><span style="background-color: initial; font-size: 9pt; font-weight: normal; font-family: AdvTT31ea7dbe; font-style: italic;">infection. It therefore occurs most commonly at the apex of a&nbsp;</span><span style="background-color: initial; font-size: 9pt; font-weight: normal; font-family: AdvTT31ea7dbe; font-style: italic;">nonvital tooth. In addition to caries, it can also result from&nbsp;</span><span style="background-color: initial; font-size: 9pt; font-weight: normal; font-family: AdvTT31ea7dbe; font-style: italic;">trauma. These two mechanisms may lead to necrosis of the&nbsp;</span><span style="background-color: initial; font-size: 9pt; font-weight: normal; font-family: AdvTT31ea7dbe; font-style: italic;">pulp cavity and may subsequently spread to the tooth apex,&nbsp;</span><span style="background-color: initial; font-size: 9pt; font-weight: normal; font-family: AdvTT31ea7dbe; font-style: italic;">with development of a periapical granuloma or periapical</span></div><i><span style="font-size: 9pt; font-family: AdvTT31ea7dbe;"><div style="text-align: justify;"><span style="background-color: initial; font-weight: normal; font-size: 9pt;">abscess&nbsp;</span><span style="background-color: initial; font-weight: normal; font-size: 9pt;">.
